was that sexual harassment? how to create healthy workplaces. please join allegra fishel & a diverse group of organizations & presenters on this free webinar.
thursday, 3--4pm et. register at: https://tiny.cc/now1018 confused about what constitutes sexual harassment and what doesnтАЩt? do you want to do the right thing, but unsure of how to proceed? are you wondering if the #metoo movement means that any romantic relationship at work is automatically considered sexual harassment?
during this webinar, national experts will explain the nuances of sexual harassment in layman terms.
attorneys and advocates will also describe tools and tips to create harassment-free cultures in diverse settings.
---what are the additional considerations when the victim is a woman of color or gender nonconforming? ---what if the victim is undocumented?
learn how to go beyond legal requirements to create cultures where every employee is treated with respect, and therefore better performing. q&a afterward.

тАЬmy #weshallbeheard story... the past few weeks have been very hard for me. listening to the testimony, i went through many emotions as has been the case over the past few years. i was sexually assaulted in a medical facility on thanksgiving day. it will be 4 years this coming thanksgiving. he took so much from me including thanksgiving day itself, as i have not celebrated since. it is always so hard for woman to have the courage to come forward with their story, just to be shot down and questioned. i chose to report it right away and even though it's been years, he has never lost his job. the message that that sends to me is it's okay for even a medical professional to do this. every detail of my life has been questioned. i have nothing in my past that i am at all ashamed of.  i havenтАЩt done anything to deserve his criminal act against me and then to be violated again by the questions they ask. what i have done or not done in my life is my business. this was never okay with me, and i was unconscious. even the detective seemed annoyed when he got the call and had to come to the police department early on thanksgiving morning to take my statement. he felt the need to tell me at least three times! it felt like he wanted me to know i shouldnтАЩt have interrupted his day with family while no one cared about mine. my fight continues.." #womensmarchonphiladelphia #metoo #wmop #wmo2019 #weshallbeheardstory #weshallbeheard #nomore #yourvoicehaspower #yourvoicematters #ibelieveyou #believesurvivors #actvism #marchforyourrights #feminist #werise #womenpowerment #speakingmytruth #powertothepolls #phillywomenrally

тАЬmy #weshallbeheard story... the past few weeks have been very hard for me. listening to the testimony, i went through many emotions as has been the case over the past few years. i was sexually assaulted in a medical facility on thanksgiving day. it will be 4 years this coming thanksgiving. he took so much from me including thanksgiving day itself, as i have not celebrated since. it is always so hard for woman to have the courage to come forward with their story, just to be shot down and questioned. i chose to report it right away and even though it is been years, he has never lost his job. the message that that sends to me is it is okay for even a medical professional to do this. every detail of my life has been questioned. i have nothing in my past that i am at all ashamed of.  i havenтАЩt done anything to deserve his criminal act against me and then to be violated again by the questions they ask. what i have done or not done in my life is my business. this was never okay with me, and i was unconscious. even the detective seemed annoyed when he got the call and had to come to the police department early on thanksgiving morning to take my statement. he felt the need to tell me at least three times! it felt like he wanted me to know i shouldnтАЩt have interrupted his day with family while no one cared about mine. my fight continues.." #womensmarchonphiladelphia #metoo #wmop #wmo2019 #weshallbeheardstory #weshallbeheard #nomore #yourvoicehaspower #yourvoicematters #ibelieveyou #believesurvivors #actvism #marchforyourrights #feminist #werise #womenpowerment #speakingmytruth #powertothepolls #phillywomenrally

text:
ЁЯОА cosplay is not consent ЁЯОА
.
as a cosplayer, i feel very strongly about the safety and comfort of attendees and fellow cosplayers at events. i created this artwork to kind of touch on that. i have had inappropriate touching/behavior done to me by photographers, cosplayers, and attendees.
.
many attendees have groped me during pictures. cosplayers have followed me around, trying to get into my area of personal space, obviously coming on to me and making me feel uncomfortable and followed, even though i made it clear i wanted to lose them/was not at all interested. photographers have thought itтАЩs okay to say things in an overt sexual tone about me in front of my boyfriend. about me. iтАЩve also had photographers touch my body or greet me in ways they think is okay because they тАЬknow meтАЭ and we are тАЬfriendsтАЭ. (obviously @cflo.tography is not included in this because she is an angel, and if you want to shoot with an amazing photographer who always ensures youтАЩre comfortable and feel safe, she is the one!! тЭдя╕ПтЭдя╕П)
.
my cosplays are my choice. no matter how revealing they are, no matter which character i am, no matter how long or short my skirt/shorts are, you are not allowed to touch me without my consent. or follow me around the event and make me feel uncomfortable. or say overtly sexual things to me.
.
this movement is very important to me, and itтАЩs important to me that people are safe. if you feel unsafe or recognize youтАЩre in an unsafe situation, please reach out to convention/event security. theyтАЩre there to help! if that might not be an option, or you donтАЩt feel comfortable, pull a friend aside and explain the situation. if you guys ever see me at a con and youтАЩre in an uncomfortable situation and arenтАЩt sure what to do, even if we have never met before, please come up to me. pretend you know me, and if you can, secretively tell me whatтАЩs going on. i will help you in any way i can. .
#cosplayisnotconsent #metoo #art #sewing #cosplay #costume #cosplayer #cosplaygirl #cosplaygirlsofinstagram #conventions #events #hobby #besafe #consent #crafting #havefun

text:
dear white women, we need to be better.

it's not enough to talk about intersectionality in our safe spaces. it's not enough to post about ourselves or our mothers or grandmothers marching for civil rights. 
because what we are doing when we leave those spaces is contradictory.

i'm talking to the white women like the lady who stood in the doorway of an apartment building blocking a black man from entering because she "felt unsafe" - who proceeded to call the police on a man who lived in said building.

i'm talking to the white women like the woman who started a business with a racist slur in the name - who when she was informed that that word was a slur, proceeded to make a live video crying about how she didn't know it was a slur, and apologizing to her customers, but ultimately saying that since she didn't know that word was a slur it is okay for her to use it. 
i'm talking to the white women who hear about sexual assault and rape cases, who proceed to make jokes on social media about it, or to talk about how not all men commit sexual assault.

i'm talking to the white women who successfully protest pipelines going near their homes, but don't support indigenous people doing the exact same thing because "well, we need oil!"
i'm talking to the white women who proudly talk about their history supporting civil rights (marching with dr. king!) but still give stink-eye to the woc spending their ebt next to them at the grocery store.

i'm talking to the white women who "prefer to stay out of politics" and "just want to think about positive things" - that's white privilege and you are taking advantage of it.

i'm talking to the white women who see posts about not wearing cultures as costumes at halloween, but dress their daughters up as pocahontas anyway because "she really wants to and i don't want to talk about all that stuff with her yet, she's a child!!" you. are. part. of. the. problem. 
this is not being allies. 
the correct response to being told you are using a racial slur is to apologize to the person hurt by that word, and to immediately stop using that word. don't center yourself. it's not about you.
(cont. in comment)

text: in the era of #metoo josie rourke has reimagined #shakespeare #measureformeasure that questions whether men and women that do the same thing are judged differently. the play opens with @j_a_lowden assuming delegated authority from the duke and charging claudio with the draconian offence of fornication out of wedlock. @wellhayley plays claudioтАЩs sister isabella who has to decide whether to give up her life in order to save her brother. #hayleyatwell gives a beautifully controlled performance as the defiantly chaste novice whilst #jacklowden with his soft scottish burr is captivating as the tyrannical purist. this is the traditional interpretation of the play as an abuse of power by politicians. however with a flash of light we are suddenly transported to a modern day court complete with text messages and selfies. now, the roles have been reversed and the play repeated but this time with a male novice and a female deputy. rourke has opted to dispense with the religiosity of the original text for a secular interpretation with angelo as a reformed addict (and seemingly chaste as part of some unexplained cult). ultimately the message is that power corrupts irrespective of gender. it is an ingenious concept executed with aplomb even if purists may find that too much of the plot, humour and exacting arguments have been jettisoned to accommodate the retelling. the supporting cast are uniformly excellent with special mention to a scene-stealing performance from @jackie_clune as a russian pompey in the second act. the minimalistic set enables a swift transition between scenes and peter mckintosh again proves adept at designing for the small @donmarwarehouse stage. this is rourkeтАЩs penultimate production at #donmarwarehouse and i canтАЩt wait to see her final show. #theatre #theater #theatregeek #westend #broadway #setdesign #lightingdesign #drama #theatrelife #london #theatrearts #theatreland #coventgarden #londontheatrereviews

text:
nuestra amiga lorena, @aguilore__ nos env├нo el siguiente comentario: "la mujer que fui" es un libro que vale la pena leer  porque a trav├йs de la historia de elizabeth, la protagonista, reconocemos en nosotras los efectos que ha dejado la cultura machista y patriarcal.
aunque el libro trata de violencia intrafamiliar, tambi├йn nos remite a la violencia presente en la educaci├│n que recibimos y que nos lleva a sentir culpa cuando no vivimos para hacer felices a los dem├бs y a la sensaci├│n de no merecer nada gratuitamente.
nos han educado para sentir culpa, pero inconscientemente  sabemos que podemos y debemos rebelarnos frente a ese papel subordinado. 
esta violencia cultural no se manifiesta en golpes, pero nos llena de sentimientos de culpa cuando queremos vivir como protagonistas de nuestra propia vida.
el libro me provoc├│ m├║ltiples sensaciones f├нsicas...me dol├нan la piel y los ├│rganos, tanto por la empat├нa que me provocaba el dolor de elizabeth, como por el hecho de sentirme parte de esta historia de violencia cultural contra las mujeres y que todas hemos vivido y naturalizado. muchas gracias por el libro"

text:
i was a rapper when i was in high school...like free-styling at lunch time and carrying my rhyme book everywhere i went type-of-rapper.  i probably spent more time writing flows than doing class work and definitely skipped more than my share of class so i could make it to a studio...not proud of that but it happen ЁЯд╖ЁЯП╜тАНтЩВя╕П. i donтАЩt know if i was any good but it didnтАЩt matter.  it was my outlet, my safe place.  things like that are needed for the hard-headed hooligan that i was.  i recorded my first demo when i was 17 and i swear i thought i was gonna get signed to a major label the very next day ЁЯджЁЯП╜тАНтЩВя╕П. uhhh...that didnтАЩt happen.
.
.
i actually didnтАЩt learn how to play guitar til much later in my life.  i taught myself how to play and started writing тЬНЁЯП╛songs (ballads) for other artists, until eventually i got the nerve to sing them myself.  writing, writing, writing.  seems like when i couldnтАЩt find the words in my own life i always found them in songs.  isnтАЩt that what creativity and art is suppose to do...speak for us, even when we canтАЩt.  now back to writing, writing, writing...and maybe i still keep a rhyme book ЁЯШЙЁЯУЦ тЬНЁЯП╛ЁЯО╡ЁЯОз
.

text:
i wrote this exactly a year ago. and it is still relevant today: 
i want to be treated like a person.

i want to be able to reach out to a cool guy i can see myself being friends with without them immediately thinking something romantic or sexual. i want them to respect me and still be able to hang with me when i say i am looking for friendship. 
i don't want to be doubted in my abilities. i want to bring ideas to the table and have them taken seriously. i don't want to be interrupted. i don't want to be talked over or looked over. i don't want to be called a bitch when i stand up for myself or when i'm direct when i speak.

i want to be seen as someone with value for my brain. i don't want to be constantly judged for my appearances, because i have so much more to offer than that.

don't fucking tell me that i need to have children right away. that a man has to be the provider in a family. that everything revolves around the male in my life. that i am not enough as a woman with dreams and goals, whether a man be in my life or not. 
see me for me.

#metoo #femenist #femalepower #thefutureisfemale #selflove #stepupmen

text:
another thing that's been so helpful to me in my own journey of healing from childhood sexual assault and incest has been to claim my shadow.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
our shadow is all those parts of ourselves that we've been taught weren't acceptable. had to be hidden.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
they become the parts of our souls -- our psyches -- that we're afraid of.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
but guess what? we can't pretend away reality. not possible.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
and a lot of what we're afraid of is our own power. our brilliance. our beauty. our much-ness. our big-ness.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
"the message we get from this hidden place is simple: there is something wrong with me. i'm not okay. i'm not lovable. i'm not deserving. i'm not worthy." ("the dark side of the light chasers," by debbie ford)таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
when we live and work and love from a place of believing something's wrong with us, that we're square pegs/round holes, when we are not enough ... that is exactly what we'll get back.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
but when we begin claiming our shadows, we begin claiming our power.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
and if there ever was a time for claiming our power ... it's now, folks.таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА
таАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаАтаА

text:
in 1926, three rooms with connecting tunnels within and underneath the great sphinx of giza were violated, condemned with concrete and sealed shut. there are photographs of work men inside these rooms & underground passage-ways, just ask egyptian director of antiquities zahi hawass. roman royalty would rent ($$$) these sphinx rooms to nobility 365 nights a year because it was believed that these rooms would bestow anyone who slept inside them with prophetic dreams. by marketing the sphinx rooms as dream incubators at great cost, so they thought, the roman elite could benefit greatly by keeping secret the knowledge of the great sphinxтАЩs underground тАЬromanтАЭ hotel. ЁЯФ║ЁЯЫ╕ЁЯМК
as a child, i was baptized by mormons and placed into the boy scouts of america program. not only was i violently raped and routinely molested, but forced to witness other boys being raped as well by sadistic, respected mormon authorities. i had great trouble sleeping as a kid...trauma is very tricky.. after loosing my friend chris allegedly to suicide at a young age, and being unable to reconcile an innocent soul cast into eternal darkness, i sought expression & picked up my older brothers guitar. my father gave me my first lesson, to help in grieving chris who was a guitar player (he supposedly hanged himself in the closet with an instrument cable). i started randomly dreaming about the giza pyramids & the great sphinx with a crown of thorns placed upon its head(for all u freudians out there: freemason inspired mormon doctrine+disneyтАЩs тАЬaladdinтАЭ cia magic carpet ride program?), and eventually sank into a very dark and lonesome sub-conscious rabbit hole goose chase to finally confront this golden egg like forgotten shadow trauma demon -twenty years later. ЁЯжЛ
but now we are awake. 
all is not in everything 
but it is all-important to keep awake.
also, we have been working on a new single that i am violently proud ofЁЯФе

text:
itтАЩs hard being the worst one in the class but youтАЩll only get better by trying.
.
i was <am> terrible at math. i would breakout in hives if i had to solve a problem on the board. i relied on the free answers in the back of the book for homework assignments (you youngins donтАЩt know what iтАЩm talking about but my 30s ladies remember!). it just didnтАЩt come naturally to me at all. i could tell by the pace my classmates worked at that i was definitely missing something. so you know what i did?
.
i stayed after school for tutoring in high school even though i really didnтАЩt like the teacher. i did homework that wasnтАЩt required. i did every extra credit assignment. i tried my absolute hardest in every one of those classes. i easily couldтАЩve thrown in the towel and said screw it i donтАЩt like it, iтАЩm not any good at it, iтАЩm embarrassed to do it in front of my peers, iтАЩm not gonna pursue a field in math, etc. but no. i busted my butt and graduated in the top 10 of my class.
.
how could the trajectory of my life changed if i hadnтАЩt kept trying? my gpa wouldтАЩve suffered, my college options wouldтАЩve been more limited, i wouldтАЩve built a precedent that just because itтАЩs hard you quit.
.
we are all the тАЬworstтАЭ at some time but we will never get better if we donтАЩt try. so what if you have to work twice as hard at __________?? we do what we have to do with blinders on and focus only on our goal. not where everyone else is.
.
hereтАЩs to being the best тАЬworstтАЭ we can be this week and refusing to give up.ЁЯТЩ

text:
тАЬin recent years, a new wave of state and local activity has transformed minimum wage policy in the u.s. as of august 2018, ten large cities and seven states have enacted minimum wage policies in the $12 to $15 range. dozens of smaller cities and counties have also enacted wage standards in this range. these higher minimum wages, which are being phased in gradually, will cover well over 20 percent of the u.s. workforce. with a substantial number of additional cities and states poised to soon enact similar policies, a large portion of the u.s. labor market will be held to a higher wage standard than has been typical over the past 50 years.

these minimum wage levels substantially exceed the previous peak in the federal minimum wage, which reached just under $10 (in todayтАЩs dollars) in the late 1960s. as a result, the new policies will increase pay directly for 15 to 30 percent of the workforce in these cities and as much as 40 to 50 percent of the workforce in some industries and regions. by contrast, the federal and state minimum wage increases between 1984 and 2014 increased pay directly for less than eight percent of the applicable workforce.

this report examines the effects of these new policies. although minimum wage effects on employment have been much studied and debated, this new wave of higher minimum wages attains levels beyond the evidential reach of most previous studies. moreover, city-level policies might have effects that differ from those of state and federal policies. yet, most of the empirical studies of minimum wages focus on the state and federal-level policies. the literature on the effects of city-level minimum wages is much smaller. our report helps fill these gaps.тАЭ
.
.
.

note: the above pronouns are interchangeable as anyone can be the victim of sexual assault/harassment. тЬи
тАв
my apologies for the lack of posts the past few days, i have been reeling from an experience with sexual harassment i dealt with and the subsequent fall out. being a sexual assault survivor three times over, i am hypersensitive to the pervasive and systemic rape culture that defines our society. and i refuse to put up with it... sometimes that means i get into uncomfortable conversations with (mostly) men who are incapable of being confronted. тЬи
тАв
you can read all about it in my latest blog post (link in bio), but what has struck the biggest cord with me are the reactions to my speaking out. тЬи
тАв
overall, most of my interactions have been overwhelmingly positive with people from different circles taking the time to message me their words of support or to share their own experiences with sexual harassment, many of which society turned a blind eye to. тЬи
тАв
but there have also been the expected responses (which, sadly not shockingly, have only been from men) coming forward to question my speaking out. to attempt to shame me into silence. to plead for consideration of the assailantтАЩs future/feelings/reputation. and iтАЩve had enough of it. тЬи
тАв
every time someone defends an assailant, be it for sexual harassment, sexual assault, or anywhere in between, they are negating the trauma and  devastating changes the victim faced, faces, and will continue to face for the coming years. тЬи
тАв
someone who chooses to violate, harass, or harm another human being does not deserve anonymity. they are not owed sympathy for all they stand to lose as a result of their choices. they are not the victims in these scenarios. ever. тЬи
тАв
iтАЩm sad. iтАЩm enraged. iтАЩm scared. i feel hopeless. i feel a myriad of emotions because of how broken our world is. how this is a socially acceptable response. how iтАЩm an outlier for taking a stand and saying enough. i feel all of these things, but i will never stop raising my voice for the voiceless. тЬКЁЯП╗тЬи
тАв
if you or someone you know is struggling as the result of sexual harassment or abuse please reach out. if you donтАЩt know where to go, message me. тЬи #metoo

text:
first things first. this is going to be completely your choice. i can't tell you what to do and you wouldn't want me to anyway. that being said setting boundaries in your life is going to be one of the most important thing you do. if you allow abusers to be in your life that have never taken responsibility then the end result will not be good. but i will help you break it down so you can decide for yourself. 
1. has this person taken full responsibility for what they did to you and they 100% acknowledge that it was wrong? or is it not talked about, addressed, or acknowledged?

2. if they haven't taken responsibility for what they did then ask yourself.. why do you want them in your life? because they are family and you don't want to cause problems? because you are afraid that you will lose them? if that's the case then ask yourself, do i really want someone in my life that has violated me, abused me, disrespected me, hasn't taken responsibility, continues to disrespect me, and acts like there's no issue?

3. how does it truly make you feel to be around this person? if it causes you any anxiety, uneasiness, or triggering feelings then there's your answer. allowing someone into your life that you feel this way around isn't worth the stress. you have every right to be selective with who you allow into your life especially if they have abused you in the past. protect your energy, your happiness, and your boundaries. just because they are "family" doesn't allow them to have a presence in your life. family is who you choose to call familyтЭдя╕П

text:

thank you to tarana burke who orchestrated this entire movement as well as alyssa milano who helped spread the word and all the other wonderful people who used their platform to speak out. #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #thegeminiproject #consent #endrapeculture #stopvictimblaming #change #wedemandjustice #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #survivorculture
